    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Style produced in ceramics at Sultanabad (modern Arak, Iran) that reached its peak as a style in the 13th and 14th centuries. Favorite types were minai (a method that preserved colors through firing), lustreware, faience in green and dark blue tones, often with molded ornamentation, and tiles richly decorated in lustre.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>為一種發祥於蘇丹納巴德的陶器風格，於西元十三、十四世紀期間發展鼎盛。較為人所喜愛的陶器種類有米奈（一種運用焙燒來維持陶器色彩的製作方法）、虹彩陶、綠色與深藍色調的彩陶，以及極具光澤的瓷磚。彩陶上通常附有用鑄模製作而成的裝飾。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
